author: @jomakaze
textdisplay:
Don't fully understand the video? No worries, it's way too niche. Here's the explanation of each line:

Thie video is a parody of this Wolf of Wallstreet scene:
https://youtu.be/wM6exo00T5I

This video criticizes the Wonderland protocol. Learn more here:
https://medium.datadriveninvestor.com/defi-wonderland-is-a-scam-3f5f448006a7

0:12 That bag is a bag of LSD. Apparently, tech employees are known to microdose on LSD. However, the amount this guy took is definitely a whole trip and not micro for filming purposes.
0:19 "...part of your DAO". DAO means decentralized autonomous organization. Usually run by a whole community, but... not really. This is why the DAO founder says, "fuck the community."
0:45 LP means liquidity provider. Usually, a DeFi project requires you to deposit money in it to make use of it, just like how you deposit money in a bank. For example, a lending protocol will allow you to lend money to other borrowers. So you're adding liquidity into the project, so you're an LP, liquidity provider.
1:04 Su Zhu is Zhu Su; he's a very successful crypto trader https://twitter.com/zhusu
1:44 Olympus and Wonderland are decentralized reserve currency projects, but some might say it's only to obfuscate a Ponzi game. Technically this project is supposed to bring stability into their native token by being backed by various crypto assets. So if you think the crypto assets like ETH and BTC are too volatile, then you can buy OHM (Olympus tokens) to stabilize the price since it's backed by a multitude of crypto tokens. This is kind of similar to how stablecoins are backed by real USD. But he's questioning why is USD the "stable" currency? Who knows, if we break out into a civil war, the USD dollar might become shit, so what is stability anyways?
1:55 Anything can be a store of value as long as there's a demand for it and it's limited. For example, Hermes Birkin bags are very sought after, like Rolex watches.
2:01 There are many DeFi projects in the space, most of them are just ways to get users to add liquidity to their project, unfortunately. They would have many tactics to mask their true intentions.
2:12 DeFi 2.0 protocols are a new wave of projects. Olympus/Wonderland are a part of that wave. This video explains DeFi 2.0 very well: https://youtu.be/l0vRTi8_FRk
2:20 This is how decentralized reserve currency projects work (Olympus/Wonderland); they're trying to put a lot of different coins into the treasury so their native token will be backed by those coins rather than the US dollar.
2:34 You tend to get an extremely high APY in DeFi projects, but they're clearly not sustainable
2:56 "another staking reward." Many times, the projects want to keep their native token price high so it's more attractive to users. To do that, they want the users to hold their tokens and not sell them off. So they would create these staking rewards to reward people who do not sell off their tokens.
3:20 Scam projects often have founders dump their native tokens on their users while the price is still high
3:34 Sifu is a co-founder of Wonderland who took $5.5M from the treasury. https://www.coindesk.com/tech/2022/02/01/address-linked-to-wonderlands-sifu-cashes-out-28m-worth-of-ether/

Hope that helps!

author: @meihui4761
textdisplay: Maybe three years late, but typo on bayesian solution. Bayesian formula for P(STD|+ve)= P(+ve|STD) *  P(STD)/P(+ve) . We are given P(+ve|STD)=99% and P(STD)=1% (1% people of all of this has STD). We need to find the probability of P(+ve). We know from 1% of people that has std, 99% will test positive. We also know for those who doesn't have STD , 1% of them will test positive. So P(+ve)= 1%x99% +99%*1%. the + typo is fix!  plug and chug to give you 50%.

author: @lauritammi4598
textdisplay:
Core points summarized:

1 INTERNSHIP // likely to be hired after it; technical degree helpful

2 SQL // Asked by every company

3 METRICS (Success & tracking) // Know data sources & what to measure - you‚Äôre the expert!

E.g.: APP UI change
a) SUCCESS metrics -> Active Users
b) TRACKING metrics -> Time spent & Videos watched / user; Forced quits (bugs); Videos uploaded

A/B TESTING -> Control and experimental groups, reduce risks

4 IPYTHON, TABLEAU, R or EXCEL // Manipulate, visualize and interpret data

5 COMMUNICATION // Clear public speaking & writing + Simplified presentations (PPT)

+6 PREDICTIVE MODELLING // Not essential, adds coolness & credibility
Useful: Forecasting goals (e.g. finance), recommendation systems

KEY QUOTE: If you made an interesting analysis, but no one‚Äôs there to read your analysis, did you really make an analysis?

But here's the thing: If you made an interesting analysis, but no one is there to read your analysis, did you really make an analysis?

This is a great point, when joined with other points mentioned in the video, basically the important thing is to convey the right information in the right way to the right people.

Right information: Information that the audience are allowed to know about, and are relevant to them.
Right way: Best using graphics and great presentation style and attractive way of presenting them (whether by talking or by written forms).
Right people: People who make decisions or will gain something from the information you give them, or simply, people who should get the information for some reason. Depends on purpose as well.

As I roll into 39 years old best advice I can give what looks to be a younger guy is to go for the fun girl 100% of the time. You will often look back & wish you had gone that route when you are stuck with boring old Nelly for the 45th year because she was "the responsible one". We always look back & wish we had done more or had more fun, many people in the late years often realize the safe route was boring & actually the most problematic route since you also more than likely got with someone that has too high of standards & now you both are miserable & you made some miserable kids & worst case scenario you start a multi-generational chain of miserable people.

I'm just here to listen to tinder tips but my dude if you are enjoying someone's company that's pretty rare & don't toss them out because of their background or because they don't make enough money. But dude go for the fun girl you won't look back & regret it when you have car trouble or are stuck in traffic for 5 hours & she fun girl is making up road games & the responsible girl is bitching about you're hair style & parents.

Cheers for this man best of luck.

author: @sanjogh777
textdisplay: @@malcorub Yeah, I get to face the clients and business vendors and we need to understand the same business problems that Data Scientists, Insight Analysts and Project managers need to understand but our job is to provide them the correct data, make Data Pipelines and refresh the datamart for the dashboards etc. But I feel like a data tech support for the rest of the project team. Also involved in working with legacy system in Teradata and modernizing it with the latest Big Data tools. But I am slowly learning the Data Analyst / Scientist work as well. That is where the "sexy" part of the work revolves around. Data Engineering is not a sexy job but it is one of the most important positions in a company.

author: @malcorub
textdisplay: @@sanjogh777  As long as you like working with data there is hope.  I am a data analyst/report developer, I rely on my D.E's (who get paid more than I do) heavily to keep the data infrastructure going, for data pipelines and building complex data models and without you guys, my job would be so much harder or dare I say, IMPOSSIBLE.  Like Jona said at the end of the video and as you mentioned in your comment, don't limit yourself.  Dabble in the data analyst, PM and data scientists side.  It's much more satisfying when you understand and can derive meaning from the data you are working with which many times, at least in my world, the DE's don't or choose not too.

This might be a better code for you if you are going with floyds triangle
def find_duplicate_number(nums):
try:
tortoise = nums[0]
hare = nums[0]


while True:
tortoise = nums[tortoise]
hare = nums[nums[hare]]
if tortoise == hare:
break


ptr1 = nums[0]
ptr2 = tortoise
while ptr1 != ptr2:
ptr1 = nums[ptr1]
ptr2 = nums[ptr2]

return ptr1
except IndexError:
raise ValueError("There are no duplicates")

def get_user_input():
while True:
try:
input_numbers = input("Enter a list of numbers separated by spaces: ")
nums = list(map(int, input_numbers.split()))
return nums
except ValueError:
print("Error: Please enter a valid list of integers.")


try:
nums = get_user_input()

if len(nums) == 0:
print("Error: Please enter at least one number.")
else:
result = find_duplicate_number(nums)
print("The duplicate number is:", result)

except ValueError as e:
print(str(e))

author: @saytheobvioustwitter2583
textdisplay:
1. Developing the specifications requires someone who knows the application - who has done that job professionally.
2. Designing the algorithm requires someone who knows mathematical and computer science techniques of processing data.
3. Writing the program requires someone who knows the programming language and how to translate the steps in the algorithm into code.
These are 3 distinct responsibilities requiring 3 distinct skills.
Having one person do all 3 minimizes the number of people but at the cost of the degradation of all 3.
The best way to have all 3 people is to have enough work to keep all 3 busy.
I learned math when I was 6 months old and my father taught me how to count to 20 then how to do arithmetic.
It also helps if you start young and have parents who let you pursue your interests.

author: @TheCackling

There have onther way to do so, and generate one point only use the random function once : )
1: Take 1 as fixed radius, Hand choose a circle angle N ( any angle value with in (0, 180] )
Loop: (Reapet 2~3, get as many point as possible)
2: Use uniformly distributed random function generate number 0~1 and multiply it by N as random angle
3: Draw the point on polar coordinate system, format: (radius, angle)
4: Calculate the distance between two adjacent points and add them up to approximate Arc length ("adjacent " can be done easily by ordering the x, y value of coordinate)
5: Because: Arc length = N/180¬∑œÄr, and r = 1; so: œÄ ‚âà approximate Arc length * 180 / N
More point we have, the smaller N we use, better the approximation we get, as this kind of prerequisite the only thing we can do is approximation.

I tried implementing this in C#, and so far, it's been working fine.

This is my code :

using System;
using System.Collections.Generic;
using System.Linq;
using System.Text;
using System.Threading.Tasks;

namespace Calculate_Pi
{
class Program
{
static void Main(string[] args)
{
Console.WriteLine("Enter the number of points:");
int numPoints = int.Parse(Console.ReadLine());
double pi = EstimatePi(numPoints);
Console.WriteLine($"Estimated value of pi: {pi}");

Console.WriteLine("Press Enter to exit...");
while (Console.ReadKey().Key != ConsoleKey.Enter)
{
// Keep looping until the Enter key is pressed
}
}

static double EstimatePi(int numPoints)
{
Random random = new Random();
int pointsInsideCircle = 0;
int pointsInsideSquare = 0;

for (int i = 0; i < numPoints; i++)
{
double x = random.NextDouble();
double y = random.NextDouble();

double distance = x * x + y * y;

if (distance <= 1)
{
pointsInsideCircle++;
}
pointsInsideSquare++;

}

double piEstimate = 4.0 * pointsInsideCircle / pointsInsideSquare;
return piEstimate;

}
}
}

author: @xnadave
textdisplay: When I conduct interviews, I intentionally ask questions that don't lend themselves to something like Leetcode. Typically, I pick a problem that we're currently working on for a real-world app and see how the candidate approaches it. I don't expect a perfect response, but how they think about things, what kinds of resources they'd use, etc. tell a lot about how well that person will fit with the team.

author: @tarekmoneimsaid
textdisplay:
After working for years with Java, I'm really enjoying learning Kotlin. It doesn't have as steep a learning curve as Scala or Clojure (pure funcional languages).

Instead, it feels like an improvement over Java, with some very welcome features, such as the usual syntactic sugar (with the ability of creating DSLs, a neat feature), extension functions (no more Util classes), better functional programming support (at least more than lambdas and streams), etc...

I'm mostly using it for personal projects, still figuring out the Kotlin way of doing things, embracing these improvements to write more concise code. It's fun :)

author: @hitbox7422
textdisplay: I actually just like logic. I like how two simple inputs in a binary adder can represent the sum of 2 arbitrary numbers. I like how, viewed on a transistor level, absurdly complex RAM is, but at the same time when you understand it, it becomes trivial and almost natural on how each component works. So yes, iam one of those people who like to program just for the sake of it. I learned python because I love the way single line expressions work like clockwork in a beautiful scheme of actions. I learned react because I see a button on a web page and imagine what amount of state-layers are behind it making it work like it does. I can observe a website and almost instantly recreate the entire codebase of it in my mind, because I just see how those components are expressions of basic data structures. Logic itself can be an expression of creativity, not just the result of it.

author: @HansBezemer
textdisplay:
One of my first programs - one which survives until this day - was a nuclear bomb simulator. In 1984 I digitized the tables and graphs of "The Effects of Nuclear Weapons" report by the Atomic Energy commission and wrote a 16K Minimal BASIC program. Really fun to do- although it took me ages to get it right.

Nowadays it still exists as a Forth program - written in my own Forth dialect. I always wanted to write my own tools. It took me almost 15 years from typing my very first BASIC statement to get to that point. And yes, the thing is free - I never saw myself making money with it - but to be honest: I didn't make it for humanity. It was simply fun to do it.

Never was much of a humanitarian to begin with - if so, I wouldn't be a programmer, but I'd do some odd jobs in an African orphanage or something. I'm happy being a programmer. Never wanted to be anything else.

author: @carlosquinones7560
textdisplay:
As an experienced, self-taught Python programmer, I agree. I wouldn't really wanna do programming for another company because doing projects that other companies want takes away the magic.
If you do your own programs for your own sake, on the other hand, that's when you start thinking like a real-world problem-solver. You gotta start small, but always do it for yourself, no matter how trivial, or how stupid your project is. There is a lot to be learned from this. I personally created a Day Trading bot that Day trades all day, every day on Robinhood and I also created a security camera program with OpenCV used as a motion detector to take images of anyone who enters my room, save the image, then immediately shutdown the computer. I plan on integrating him with my own personal virtual assistant (Ultron) so he can upload the image via Whatsapp and turn off the Day Trading bot in case something goes wrong when I'm not home. The security cam is actually supposed to protect my Day Trading bot while I am not home by shutting down the computer upon intrusion.

I'm actually working on a Whatsapp UI in the form of a virtual assistant named Ultron who can control my computer when I am away from home and chat with me through Emerson AI and soon enough I will also add the option of chatting with blenderbot as an available alternative through Ultron. Basically you would send Ultron a command via text with a reserved symbol ('!') followed by the command itself and any parameters you would like to add with the '#' symbol. Ultron then parses the text to differentiate between a text message and a command and currently sends those text messages to Emerson AI and sends his response via Whatsapp, then he runs the commands in order.

You can actually chain multiple commands together this way so they can be executed in order, such as uploading a screenshot of the computer followed by shutting down the computer or something. Its super radical!

author: @PhilippeCarphin
textdisplay:
A lot of skills I learned in my degree can be learned online by someone who is disciplined enough to do it on their own.

One thing it did give me is that we had a lot of assignments and every single one of them was in teams of two or more. During my whole degree I constantly had important things that would affect my grades depending on other people and my relationships with them. And myself always being responsible for my part in the success or failure of other people.

All that means is that if you're a self learner, one of the things you might want to self learn is collaborating with others. Even if you're the superior coder, just having a better solution doesn't mean that your teammate you got paired with is going to be down with that particular solution.

textdisplay:

am the author of one of the fastest compilers of any non trivial programming language (there are some now that can compete but not many).

def fibonacci(n):
a = []
while len(a) == 0:¬†

while len(a) == 1:
a.append(1)
while n > len(a):
a.append(a[len(a) - 1] + a[len(a) - 2])
return a[n-1]

author: @patcoston
textdisplay: What's the appeal of vi?  It seems to me that editors like VSCode, Sublime Text and Atom are far superior.  They are designed for writing code and color code based on different languages and have extensions so you can customize.  They'll warn of syntax errors, spelling errors, variables not in use, and so on. They'll also autoformat, lint check, bracket match, auto-complete code, intellisense, auto-rename matching tags, auto-close tags, and so much more.  I don't think vi does any of that, plus you have to change modes between insert, overwrite and command mode. If you forget your in command mode and start typing, suddenly you can find you've executed a long set of commands putting yourself in a weird state.

author: @meihui4761
textdisplay: Maybe three years late, but typo on bayesian solution. Bayesian formula for P(STD|+ve)= P(+ve|STD) *  P(STD)/P(+ve) . We are given P(+ve|STD)=99% and P(STD)=1% (1% people of all of this has STD). We need to find the probability of P(+ve). We know from 1% of people that has std, 99% will test positive. We also know for those who doesn't have STD , 1% of them will test positive. So P(+ve)= 1%x99% +99%*1%. the + typo is fix!  plug and chug to give you 50%.

author: @andrewninh
textdisplay: Agree that SQL, R, and Python are the most important languages for data science, but SQL is way more than just a query language. Anyone who has worked in NLP or needed to query massive datasets knows this (unless infrastructure has changed significantly). What if you want to do a calculation using columns across tables with millions or billions of rows? Are you going to query the whole table and calculate in R/Python and put back into SQL? Maybe if you want to wait around 100000x longer. 90% of the work and understanding the dataset is in SQL; Python and R are to build models (that's where the libraries come in).

author: @emmettboudreau5474
textdisplay:
Mans didnt even talk about Julia.
Julia's like R, Python, C, and MATLAB all had a disgusting baby that is suprisingly effective.
Julia's biggest weakness is that Julia isn't Python, thus the packages aren't quite there, but thanks to my work as well as other Julia developer's work, it's more and more viable every day.
We have Genie, which mirrors flask in a way, full support for IPython, via IJulia, we can manage hadoop workers, work with all of the lovely forms of sql, mysql, sqllite, postgres, etc... I'm not too sure about mongo if you're into that...
ML has come a long way, and previously it was hard to even do a test train split in Julia. There are still some issues with DataFrames, and bugs and stuff but thanks to Lathe.jl (Pkg.add("Lathe")), test train splitting and model fitting/predicting can be done in literally 3 lines.
test,train = Lathe.preprocess.TestTrainSplit(df)
model = Lathe.models.LinearRegression(train.x,train.y)
y_pred = Lathe.models.predict(model,test.x)
Boom.

author: @PhilippeCarphin
textdisplay:
A lot of skills I learned in my degree can be learned online by someone who is disciplined enough to do it on their own.

One thing it did give me is that we had a lot of assignments and every single one of them was in teams of two or more. During my whole degree I constantly had important things that would affect my grades depending on other people and my relationships with them. And myself always being responsible for my part in the success or failure of other people.

All that means is that if you're a self learner, one of the things you might want to self learn is collaborating with others. Even if you're the superior coder, just having a better solution doesn't mean that your teammate you got paired with is going to be down with that particular solution.

author: @yushi911
textdisplay: I work for the biggest national Telecom entreprise of Canada for the past 15 years. Can‚Äôt tell for other departments but we were very lucky to have our senior director‚Ä¶ a real captain on the ship! In 2008 with the economic crisis, the upper management ask for 5% lay off. He call a town hall and explain the lay off plan ‚Ä¶he also made a proposal to his team: if there is any employees welling to take a couple of months off as his goal is to not lay off any employees coz . He totally disagree with upper management decision as a professional services department and anyway when the economy will jump back, he will need to hire people. He promised that the employees who decided to take some time off, they will be on the bottom of the lay off list if we need to come to this option‚Ä¶ 11 of my colleagues volunteers to take a couples months off. We were the only techno department of 200 employees without any lay off and we go through this difficult period together. Very low turnover rate until my senior director retired‚Ä¶ then we see many colleagues quitting for new opportunities. This guy was a leader. I was new grad when I had the chance to work for him, he still an inspiration for my day to day work as a project manager.

0:09 Do Kwon actually name his daughter after his token Luna. https://twitter.com/stablekwon/status/1515501798442008577
0:23 Do Kwon said this to someone called Algod on Twitter, meaning that he isn't loaded enough to make big shorts https://twitter.com/stablekwon/status/1501551050490146816
0:47 Another Do Kwon tweet https://twitter.com/stablekwon/status/1410491186196795398?lang=en
1:09 Pictures represent his preference to UST to Luna, it'll be important later on in the video
1:12 Foreshadowing that UST will be depegged
1:52 Do Kwon hates DAI from MakerDAO, another algorithmic stablecoin.
2:46 I drew that, it's cute right?
3:09 Do Kwon tried to buy out 10B worth of bitcoin for reserves to defend UST, trying to make it a standard https://cointelegraph.com/news/we-re-already-buying-terra-founder-plans-to-obtain-10b-btc-for-reserves
3:17 A strategy to beat DAI, was to make another pool of stablecoins (on Curve) that included UST. A random article I found can explain it better probably https://medium.com/@crypto8fi/4pool-enters-the-curve-wars-e10c73a637dd

5:28 Selling all that Bitcoin to defend UST can cause a lot of sell pressure on the Bitcoin price, which can tank the crypto ecosystem as a whole
6:59 The only way Terra Luna will survive, is to give up on UST, no more stablecoin. That's the only way Terra as a blockchain can survive.
7:32 I have no idea if he played Starcraft, but he is Korean so.
8:45 This is the whole speech Do Kwon gave on twitter. https://twitter.com/stablekwon/status/1526258273820651520

author: @GarryTan
textdisplay: Thanks again for having me. The world does need better venture capitalists, so I hope people watching this do enter the business and help others start up!

author: @LeveragedFinance
textdisplay: Thanks for giving back to us on the interwebs. What skills do you look for in young 20 year old associates?

author: @GarryTan
textdisplay:
PUBG Play of the Game Being deeply strong in one or two things and generalist in everything else. Then being a good communicator and self aware. The best investors are able to think deeply about what the world needs, while also identifying people who can actually create solutions for those needs.

Personally I am looking for someone who is a believer who is right before it is obvious. That‚Äôs how we make money after all: finding things that could be the biggest outcomes.

author: @oriole8789
textdisplay: What sorts of things do you dislike about how other VCs may choose to handle things? From the points you've made, the ones that resonate the most are the "unity of the team" and "if we need to take control then we've chosen the wrong people to back" (or something to that effect). Lots of people work poorly together, but in my experience (I do lowly engineering/consultant work) you sort of have to watch them work in a natural environment (as opposed to being on their best behavior while you're there). Poor communication is probably the most common one. Whatever small problems they may have, would get multiplied by 100x at later stages. I know this sounds kind of funny, but in a subjective way, the team members have to kind of love each other yet also have the motivation/resolve to push each other's abilities. That's kind of the "dream team" haha. Rarely happens in reality. It's usually some compromise~

author: @GarryTan
textdisplay:
whatlions This is a great observation and is one of the most obvious reasons why startups are hard. Organizing talented type A people is hard. It‚Äôs remarkably like catherding.

Bad VCs treat the business like lotto scratching. The bad version of this game is people run around trying to get one billion dollar company by whatever means necessary. That is both short term greedy and hurts founders.

The good version is an iterated, infinite game where investors find great founders and help them through the worst times.

author: @oriole8789
textdisplay: @@GarryTan Thank you for responding! Your analogy makes sense. Maximum greed with minimal involvement. Lazy. It's a different ideology. Kind of like.. is money your only objective? Or are you trying to build genuine relationships with people and have profound effects on the industries you get involved in? Although I do entirely different type of work, the mistake I often see from business owners is obsession with minor stats they get from BI and forgetting to focus on "the business of the business". The thing I always end up shoving down their throats is "look, you have to serve your customers first". Customer voices + feedback have a ton of weight. My "customer-centric" ideology often clashes with other contractors who are number-centric, or who end up using finite resources to achieve something that has zero impact on conversion/growth/etc. Always fun. I keep on having to say silly stuff like "do you guys remember that you're serving actual humans?". This point seems to get lost so easily. I'm sure you guys experience similar situations. "Cat herding" is something I'll never forget, thanks haha!

author: @farouqalsalih619
textdisplay: Two Sigma has 3 technical and 3 behavioural interviews lasting an hour each.  They also have an online assessment when you apply that‚Äôs about 70 minutes long. The technical coding questions they ask you vary between LeetCode medium and hard, which is surprising because companies typically don‚Äôt ask LeetCode hard questions, especially for an interview under an hour. Furthermore, the technical coding interviews happen back to back. So you‚Äôd be sitting for 3-4 hours solving 3 LeetCode medium/hard questions with 3 different Software Engineers, under an hour each. The 3 behavioural one hour interviews also happen in one day back to back (and you only take them IF you pass the technical interviews first). Needless to say, it is super hard. So be sure to be prepared! I would also like to point out one special thing about Two Sigma, they genuinely look for skill and talent. You don‚Äôt need to have a high college GPA or super impressive resume to get the interview as long as you have demonstrated genuine skill, talent, and success in other areas.

author: @kjellandree7413
textdisplay: A hobby like youtube can be fun for a hobby, to have youtube as a job you might feel like your job is stressful and you get so much pressure from viewers, yourself, and the society itself, It doesn't seem like youtube has become a social accepted job yet, and you are expected to make x amount, no matter how much you make, the high from "the first viewer/sub gain" is slowly dropping by time. A lot of things change, a lot of pressure comes in and "ruins" a hobby. I guess what I try to tell is what you said about a hard day at work, you can relax, make youtube videos or whatever hobby you have, but when a hobby becomes work, it doesn't work like that anymore. I have been diagnosed with Social Anxiety and depression recently, have been struggling with it for yeaaaars, but no matter how long you have it or had it, most people have at least one depressive episode in their life, I would highly recommend you to talk with someone professional, it helped me a lot, but doesn't help everyone. author: @malefeministgiangilo287
textdisplay:
I wonder. Do you ever think about depression in terms of a system. Like a symbiosis. It's more marked with my condition, Schizophrenia. But really the state of the art with what science thinks is going on is brain chemistry. Basically Dopamine is different in schizophrenics. But in terms of systems, If you think about fear, as a systemic process we see something that triggers our brain to go into a different mode which manifests chemical changes, so experience provokes brain chemistry, adrenaline. Adrenaline impacts psychology. So experience impacts chemistry which impacts psychology.

It's interesting to think that this is how a lot of stuff might work with psychology and mood.

People always think about Depression now in terms of chemistry, but it's almost like the perception of brain chemistry for a depressive is you are passive. You're unlucky in terms of the brain you got doesn't work right. And you sit back and take meds because your brain works the way it works irrespective.

Does this passive attitude submit. Because if the condition is a symbiotic cycle, then the cycle for a clinical depressive will be a loop that perpetuates. So there will be no logical difference between the perception that you have no choice, and that being the reality. That you have no choice..

Because the data, the experience in the system, manifests the same result.

People always seem to think everything about the condition is a constant. And really experience is a variable. It's not going to be the complete picture because different people have different chemistry and also different psychology. So the proposition that this is like a machine would rely on chemistry and psychology in terms of response being the same, which patently it isn't. But what it does do is change one of the constants in perception from a constant to a variable. And you wonder is modulation of this variable enough to leverage mood.

Bullshit really. But they always say do practical things... Experience..

author: @malefeministgiangilo287
textdisplay:
Like you wonder, if psychology works like mathematics.. choices and variables.. Positive people. People think people with a positive attitude is nature. We were born with the nature we were born with. But like, if you think about experience and choice manifests chemistry.. If a component of positive attitude is chemistry.. Chemistry is a consequence of experience, is there a mathematical route to depression? Like abuse in kids makes emotional problems in later life..

So that's experience manifests psychology and chemical responses.. So experience manifested chemical reflexes that carried through into adulthood. That's experience that didn't need to happen. So patently that chemistry wasn't nature, that was consequence of violent experience.

Bullshit. I go off.
